{"parse":{"title":"Junction Theatre Company","pageid":52602013,"revid":803904027,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Junction Theatre Company</b> was South Australia\u2019s first professional <a href=\"/wiki/Community_theatre\" title=\"Community theatre\">community theatre</a> company, founded in 1984.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Junction Theatre Company created touring works in schools, factories and other workplaces, with an aim to \u201ccreate theatre of a high artistic quality which is accessible to those sections of the community who have not traditionally participated in theatre as an accessible option for entertainment, learning and expressing issues\u201d <sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In its early days Junction Theatre was one of the country's main proponents of work supported by the program of funding Art and Working Life,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> along with companies such as <a href=\"/wiki/Melbourne_Workers_Theatre\" title=\"Melbourne Workers Theatre\">Melbourne Workers Theatre</a> in Victoria. The Art and Working Life funding program supported projects created in partnership with Trade Unions. Through the use of its own venue, it also became known as having an important role in facilitating the work of smaller companies in South Australia <sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Junction Theatre Company\u2019s first Artistic Director was Malcolm Blaylock.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The subsequent and artistic director was Geoff Crowhurst, who was in the role until the closure of the company in 2001. Geoff Crowhurst was considered \u201cA master of making theatre work for the good of whole communities\u201d,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  and had an <a href=\"/wiki/Arts_South_Australia\" title=\"Arts South Australia\">Arts South Australia</a> Ruby Award category posthumously named in his honour for individuals who make \"an outstanding contribution to community cultural development\u201d <sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Productions by Junction Theater Company include:\n</p>\n<ul><li>The company's first production, <i>Next Year's Model</i> in 1984, about the gradual closure of the General Motors Holden plant in Woodville, Victoria <sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><i>The Keys to the Animal Room</i> by Peta Murray, 1993, about an abusive marital relationship, which received the 1994 Gold <a href=\"/wiki/AWGIE_Awards\" title=\"AWGIE Awards\">AWGIE Award</a> <sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><i>Hello Down There</i> in 1993, a play about the collapse of the <a href=\"/wiki/State_Bank_of_South_Australia\" title=\"State Bank of South Australia\">State Bank of South Australia</a>, which was named 'Best Community Theatre for 1993' in The Advertiser <sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The company's last production, <i>Love Land and Money</i>, 2002, relating to themes of reconciliation and mining industries,<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> co-presented by <a href=\"/wiki/Adelaide_Fringe_Festival\" title=\"Adelaide Fringe Festival\">Adelaide Fringe Festival</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Tandanya_National_Aboriginal_Cultural_Institute\" title=\"Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute\">Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Junction_Theatre_Company&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"New Theatre Company Formed\", The Advertiser, Sunday October 6, 1984, Page 10</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"Junction Theatre Company Annual Report 1990\", State Library of South Australia</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Geoffrey Milne, Theatre Australia (un)limited: Australian Theatre Since the 1950s, Rodopi 2004</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Don Rubin, Chua Soo Pong, Ravi Chaturvedi, The World Encyclopedia of Contemporary Theatre: Asia/Pacific, Taylor &amp; Francis 2001</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Geoffrey Milne, Theatre Australia (un)limited: Australian Theatre Since the 1950s, Rodopi 2004</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\"<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.australiacouncil.gov.au/news/media-centre/media-releases/australia-council-mourns-geoff-crowhurst/\">AUSTRALIA COUNCIL MOURNS GEOFF CROWHURST</a>\"</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/ruby-awards-have-an-art-of-glass-for-10th-anniversary/news-story/9a8dc45affee457c81ddced45df9a66f\">\"Ruby Awards have an art of glass for 10th Anniversary\"</a> The Advertiser</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/event/60962\">\"AusStage Database\" </a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://australianplays.org/playwright/CP-murken\">\"Peta Murray | Australian Plays Online\" </a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Junction Theatre Company Annual Report, 1993, pp 6</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://murraybramwell.com/?p=322\">\"The Adelaide Review, No.222, March, 2002. pp.22-23\" </a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:P_culture.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/P_culture.svg/35px-P_culture.svg.png\" width=\"35\" height=\"32\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/P_culture.svg/53px-P_culture.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/P_cultu